    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-03-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-03-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="5"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d5">
                <head>5. National Security Study Memorandum 30<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d5fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                            >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Institutional
                        Files (H-Files), Box H–141, National Security Study Memoranda, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 30. Secret; <gloss target="#t_Exdis1"
                            >Exdis</gloss>. Copies were sent to <persName corresp="#p_MRP1"
                            >Mayo</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_DBLA1"
                        >DuBridge</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1969-03-19">March 19, 1969</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of the Interior</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Agriculture</item>
                    <item>The Chairman, Atomic Energy Commission</item>
                    <item>The Director of Central Intelligence</item>
                    <item>The Administrator, Agency for International Development</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Water Development and Middle East Policy</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has requested a paper covering the economic and technological
                    aspects of the following: <list>
                        <item>—the pros and cons in current thinking about the applicability of
                            large-scale desalting in the Middle East;</item>
                        <item>—the pros and cons of proceeding with a 40-million-gallon-perday
                            desalting plant in Israel;</item>
                        <item>—the alternative approaches to water development in the Middle
                            East.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>This paper should identify ways in which the U.S. private sector is involved in
                    programs now dealing with these matters.</p>
                <p>In addition to the above report on the economic and technological aspects, a
                    paper should present alternative strategies for relating the technological track
                    to our political strategy in the area.</p>
                <p>The President has directed that the study be prepared by the <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Interdepartmental Group for Near East and that
                    the Secretary of the Interior, the Secretary of Agriculture, the Chairman of the
                    Atomic Energy Commission and the Administrator of <gloss target="#t_AID1"
                        >AID</gloss> each designate a representative to sit on the Group for this
                    purpose.</p>
                <p>These papers should be forwarded to the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                    Review Group by May 23.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
